Serves: 4

Ingredients:
  medium chicken
  butter
  salt
  pepper
  Béarnaise sauce:
    3 tbsp white wine vinegar
    3 tbsp dry white wine
    1 tsp coarsely graound black pepper
    2 shallots, finely chopped
    3 egg yolks
    1 tbsp roughly chopped tarragon
    salt
  2 tbsp finely chopped tarragon or chervil
  a squeeze of lemon juice

Pre heat the oven to 200°C.
Split the chicken along the backbone with a large kitchen knife, then push down on the breast bone with both hands to flatten the bird.
Sit over a rack in a roasting tray, brush with melted butter, season and roas for 20 minutes then lower then baste and and lower the heat to 180°C and continue for a further 40-50 minutes of until cooked and golden.

20 minutes before the end of cooking time set you new potatoes to boil in salted water and prepare the sauce.
First melt the butter in a small saucepan, skim any scum from the surface and leave to stand.
Place the crushed peppercorns, roughly chopped tarraagon, win and vnegar in a small saucepan and boil to reduce to a third of it's volume.
Allow to cool for a few minutes before whisking in the egg yolks to light.
Over a very low heat (or in a bowl over simmering water), whisk gently but constanly until the mixture thickens and becomes creamy.
Remove from the heat and whisk in the tepid butter - a few drops at a time to begin with and then faaster as the sauce emulsifies.
Don't use the milky sediment of the butter.

When all butter is incorporated, finish with a little lemon and the finely chopped herps and check seasoning.
Serve whilst still warm over a joint of chicken and new potatoes.
